## How to paginate as a client

```
# First page (no cursor)
GET /api/posts?limit=20

# Subsequent pages: take `nextCursor` from the previous response
GET /api/posts?limit=20&after=eyJjcmVhdGVkX2F0IjoiMjAyNS0wMS0xNVQxMjowMDowMFoiLCJpZCI6IjQyIn0=
```

Keep requesting until `hasMore` is `false` or `nextCursor` is `null`.

---

## Why cursor-based pagination is superior here

| Concern | OFFSET-based | Cursor-based |
|---|---|---|
| **Performance on large tables** | `OFFSET 10000` forces PostgreSQL to read and discard 10,000 rows before returning results — cost is **O(N)** per page | The `WHERE (created_at < $1 OR …)` condition hits the `(created_at DESC, id DESC)` index directly — cost is **O(1)** regardless of how deep into the table you are |
| **Consistency under writes** | A new post inserted between page 1 and page 2 shifts every row's OFFSET, causing **rows to be skipped or duplicated** across pages | The cursor is pinned to a specific row, so concurrent inserts/deletes **never cause drift** |
| **Expensive COUNT(\*)** | Required to compute `totalPages`, and `COUNT(*)` is a full table scan on unvacuumed PostgreSQL | Eliminated entirely — the N+1 trick detects the next page cheaply |
| **Trade-off** | Can jump to arbitrary pages (`page=47`) | Can only navigate forward sequentially (acceptable for feeds, infinite scroll, APIs) |

The compound cursor `(created_at, id)` is necessary because `created_at` alone is not unique — two posts can share a timestamp. Adding `id` (which is unique and monotone) makes the cursor **stable and unambiguous** even for ties.

